value.value: The district in which an individual permanently resides.
The village in which an individual permanently resides.
The country in which an individual permanently resides.
A type of tear that is spread across the surface of the eye at regular intervals with blinking, coating the eyes to keep them moist.
A type of tear produced in response to irritation from foreign particles, vapors, bright lights, or peppery substances; contains higher amounts of antibodies in comparison to other tear types.
A type of tear produced in response to negative and positive emotions; contains higher amounts of proteins and stress-related hormones in comparison to other tear types.
Capillary blood collected from a puncture site that has been warmed or treated with creams containing a hyperemic or vasodilatory agent to increase arterial blood flow.

An electrophoresis procedure, in which a sample is introduced into a capillary tube and the components are separated by the application of high voltage. Due to the large surface to volume ratio, cooling is more efficient, allowing use of higher voltages.  As a result, separation occurs more quickly and sensitivity is increased. The technique allows for separation of proteins, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates.
The fluid that is produced from the movement of whole blood across a semipermeable membrane in response to a pressure gradient, removing blood cells and large proteins.

The mucous membrane comprising the inner layer of the uterine wall; it consists of a simple columnar epithelium and a lamina propria that contains simple tubular uterine glands. The structure, thickness, and state of the endometrium undergo marked change with the menstrual cycle.
A title that describes the function of a study contact within their organization.
A non-unique textual identifier for the study contact.
A sequence of decimal digits (0-9) that is used for identifying a destination telephone line or other device in a telephone network that is used by the study contact.
A text string identifier for a location to which e-mail for the study contact can be delivered.
A physical location used by a study contact for the purpose of receiving postal mail deliveries.
A unit of mass concentration for the number of picograms of substance per cell.
A dose calculation unit expressed in milligrams per milliliter per day.
A dose calculation unit expressed in nanomoles per kilogram per day.
A technique for analyzing or identifying proteins immobilized on a filter by complementary reaction with specific antibodies.
A unit of measurement equal to the number of hours within a period of time equal to one day.
A unit of measurement equal to the number of minutes within a period of time equal to one day.
The number of breaths (inhalation and exhalation) taken within a period of time equal to thirty seconds.
A unit of catalytic activity concentration defined as the catalytic activity equal to one billionth of katal (10E-9 katal) per gram hemoglobin.
An arbitrary unit of measurement established by the European Pharmacopoeia that corresponds to 1800 Kallidinogenase Inactivator units.
A unit of mass commonly used to express the molar mass of a substance in microgram(s) per mole.
A unit of mass commonly used to express the molar mass of a substance in nanogram(s) per mole.
A unit equal to one million base pairs used as a denominator to build a derived unit expressed as a ratio.
A number representing one million paired nucleotides in a DNA or RNA sequence.

An extra rib at the cervicothoracic border with the distal extremity rounded, length less than one third of the length of the ossified portion of the first thoracic rib and no costal cartilage distal. (Makris S, Solomon HM, Clark R, Shiota K, Barbellion S, Buschmann J, Ema M, Fujiwara M, Grote K, Hazelden KP, Hew KW, Horimoto M, Ooshima Y, Parkinson M, Wise LD. Terminology of developmental abnormalities in common laboratory mammals (Version 2). Part B. Birth Defects Res B Dev Reprod Toxicol. 2009 Aug;86(4):227-327.)
An x-ray examination of the esophagus, stomach and first part of the small intestine following coating with barium solution via ingestion.
The transitional period of life between immature and mature reproductive states.
A qualitative microscopic examination of reproductive tissue sections to determine sexual maturity.
A smooth muscle neoplasm with benign characteristics that arises from the mesovarium.

A carcinoma that arises from the renal tubules in rats. It is characterized by the presence of malignant large, round to polyhedral finely granular cells with amphophilic to eosinophilic cytoplasm, numerous vacuoles, and prominent nucleoli.

An adenoma that arises from the renal tubules in rats. It is characterized by the presence of benign large, round to polyhedral finely granular neoplastic cells with amphophilic to eosinophilic cytoplasm, numerous vacuoles, and prominent nucleoli.
A malignant neoplasm that has been described in rats. It arises from pituicytes in the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

A degradative process in neurons that is typically spontaneous and is characterized by distinct membrane bound pale eosinophilic cytoplasm, dark eosinophilic globular material. It usually occurs with no discernable reaction of surrounding cells and a lack of inflammatory cells.

Cylindrical, hyaline-appearing, loosely-textured, whorled, cell-sparse structures found in the subperincurial space in peripheral nerves. (Arthur K. Asbury, M.D. Renaut Bodies: A Forgotten Endoneurial Structure. Journal of Neuropathology & Experimental Neurology, Volume 32, Issue 2, April 1973, Pages 334-343)
Increase in the number or size of aggregates.
Increase in the amount of apoptosis.
A quassinoid phytochemical isolated from the plant Brucea antidysenterica with potential antineoplastic activity. (NCI04)
The process by which the spleen becomes smaller in size or scope.
Decrease in the size of the cortex relative to the medulla.
Increase in the size of the cortex relative to the medulla.
Increase in the amount of epithelium-free areas in the thymic cortex.
Decrease in corticomedullary distinction due to changes in lymphocyte cellularity.
Presence of exogenous or endogenous hyaline material within the thymus or other organ or tissue.

label.value: Increased Number of Hypersegmented Neutrophils Present

value.value: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of a high number of hypersegmented neutrophils in a peripheral blood smear.

label.value: Experimental Organism Increased Serosa-Associated Lymphoid Clusters

value.value: Clusters of lymphocytes (including innate lymphoid cells), macrophages, plasma cells, and mast cells located immediately below, and covered by, the mesothelium. (INHAND)
